===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|icon|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|εἰκών||likeness, image, portrait|lang=grc}}. Eastern Orthodox Church sense is attested from 1833. Computing sense first recorded in 1982.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈaɪ.kən/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈaɪ.kɑːn/|lang=en}}
** {{audio|En-us-icon.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}
[[Image:Cyril_Methodius25K.jpg|right|thumb|160px|A religious icon]]

# An [[image]], [[symbol]], [[picture]], or other [[representation]] usually as an object of religious devotion.
# A religious painting, often done on wooden panels.
# A person or thing that is the best example of a certain profession or some doing.
#: ''That man is an '''icon''' in the business; he personifies loyalty and good business sense.''
# A small picture which represents something (such as an icon on a computer screen which when clicked performs some function.)
# {{context|linguistics|lang=en}} A type of noun whereby the form reflects and is determined by the [[referent]]; [[onomatopoeic]] words are necessarily all icons. See also {{term|symbol}} and {{term|index}}.
# Pictual representations of files, programs and folders on a computer.

